                <h2 class="text-4xl font-anamortee mb-2">Glen Falls</h2>
                <p class="text-xl opacity-90">The Triple Threat Hidden Gem</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
              <p class="text-xl font-medium mb-6" style="color: rgb(45, 69, 56);">
                While Dry Falls and Bridal Veil Falls attract the highway travelers, Glen Falls remains something of a local secret, requiring a bit more effort to reach but rewarding visitors with not one, but three spectacular waterfalls along a moderate 2-mile round trip hike.
              </p>

              <p class="mb-6">
                Located just a mile south of Highlands off Highway 106, Glen Falls on the East Fork of Overflow Creek offers a more intimate, wilderness experience. The trail presents you with a choice about a third of a mile in: take the left fork to reach the top of the 60-foot upper falls first, or bear right to approach from below.
              </p>

              <div class="text-white rounded-xl p-8 my-8" style="background-color: rgb(45, 69, 56);">
                <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">üåô Secret Experience</h4>
                <p class="opacity-95">
                  The best-kept secret about Glen Falls is visiting during a full moon in summer. The lack of artificial light pollution means the falls are illuminated naturally, creating an otherworldly scene that few people ever witness.
                </p>
              </div>

              <p class="mb-6">
                Most locals recommend starting with the lower trail to build up to the dramatic upper falls. The lower falls, at about 15 feet, might seem modest, but the deep pool at its base is a favorite summer swimming hole for those brave enough to face the perpetually cold mountain water.
              </p>

              <p class="mb-8">
                But it's the upper falls that truly takes your breath away. At 60 feet, this powerful cascade shoots through a narrow chute before spreading across the rock face. A wooden observation deck provides safe viewing, but adventurous hikers can carefully make their way to the rocks above the falls for a bird's eye view of the Blue Valley below.
              </p>
            </div>
          </section>

          <!-- Whitewater Falls Section -->
          <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="relative rounded-2xl overflow-hidden mb-8" style="height: 60vh;">
              <img
                src="https://res.cloudinary.com/southland-organics/image/upload/c_fill,w_1200,h_800,q_auto:best,f_auto/banyan_tree/flat_mountain/Whitewater-Falls"
                alt="Whitewater Falls - Tallest waterfall east of the Rockies"
                class="absolute inset-0 w-full h-full object-cover"
              />
              <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-t from-black/60 to-transparent"></div>
              <div class="absolute bottom-8 left-8 text-white">
                <h2 class="text-4xl font-anamortee mb-2">Whitewater Falls</h2>
                <p class="text-xl opacity-90">The Southeast's Tallest Cascade</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
              <p class="text-xl font-medium mb-6" style="color: rgb(45, 69, 56);">
                Saving the most dramatic for last, Whitewater Falls straddles the North Carolina-South Carolina border about 15 miles south of Highlands, claiming the title of the highest waterfall east of the Rocky Mountains.
              </p>

              <p class="mb-6">
                With a total drop of 811 feet through a series of cascades, Whitewater Falls is actually best experienced from both states, each offering unique perspectives of this natural wonder. From the North Carolina side, accessed via Highway 281, a quarter-mile paved trail leads to an overlook that provides the classic view of the upper 411-foot drop.
              </p>

              <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 my-8">
                <div class="rounded-lg p-6" style="background-color: rgb(245, 245, 244); border: 2px solid rgb(86, 125, 95);">
                  <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3" style="color: rgb(86, 125, 95);">üî¨ Geological Wonder</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The exposed rock face tells a billion-year-old story of continental collision and mountain building. The waterfall is actively eroding headward at about one foot every thousand years.
                  </p>
                </div>
                <div class="rounded-lg p-6" style="background-color: rgb(245, 245, 244); border: 2px solid rgb(71, 133, 169);">
                  <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3" style="color: rgb(71, 133, 169);">üì∏ Photo Challenge</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The massive scale makes it difficult to capture in a single frame. Best light occurs in mid-morning when sun illuminates the falls while leaving the forest in shade.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>

              <p class="mb-6">
                What many visitors don't realize is that there's a challenging but rewarding trail that descends 700+ steps to the base of the falls. This strenuous hike isn't for everyone‚Äîthe return trip will test your fitness level‚Äîbut those who make the journey are rewarded with a completely different perspective.
              </p>

              <p class="mb-8">
                From below, you can truly appreciate the violence with which the water strikes the rocks, creating a perpetual thunderstorm of mist and sound. The pool at the base is often shrouded in spray, creating an ever-changing pattern of rainbows on sunny days.
              </p>
            </div>
          </section>

          <!-- Seasonal Guide -->
          <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="text-white rounded-2xl p-10" style="background: linear-gradient(to bottom right, rgb(86, 125, 95), rgb(45, 69, 56));">
              <h2 class="text-3xl font-anamortee mb-8 text-center">üóìÔ∏è Seasonal Secrets and Timing</h2>

              <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-6">
                <div class="bg-white/10 rounded-lg p-6">
                  <div class="text-3xl mb-3">üå∏</div>
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Spring (Apr-Jun)</h3>
                  <ul class="text-sm opacity-90 space-y-1">
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Highest water flow</li>
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Wildflowers blooming</li>
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Thunderous sounds</li>
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Migrating birds</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-white/10 rounded-lg p-6">
                  <div class="text-3xl mb-3">‚òÄÔ∏è</div>
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Summer (Jun-Aug)</h3>
                  <ul class="text-sm opacity-90 space-y-1">
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Swimming opportunities</li>
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Lush green forests</li>
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Visit before 9 AM</li>
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Afternoon storms</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-white/10 rounded-lg p-6">
                  <div class="text-3xl mb-3">üçÇ</div>
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Fall (Sep-Nov)</h3>
                  <ul class="text-sm opacity-90 space-y-1">
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Spectacular colors</li>
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Lower water reveals rocks</li>
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Peak in mid-October</li>
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Weekdays best</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-white/10 rounded-lg p-6">
                  <div class="text-3xl mb-3">‚ùÑÔ∏è</div>
                  <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Winter (Dec-Mar)</h3>
                  <ul class="text-sm opacity-90 space-y-1">
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Ice formations</li>
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Dramatic ice palaces</li>
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Check road conditions</li>
                    <li>‚Ä¢ Proper equipment needed</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </section>

          <!-- Conservation Section -->
          <section class="mb-16">
            <div class="bg-white border-2 rounded-xl p-10" style="border-color: rgb(86, 125, 95);">
              <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 text-center" style="color: rgb(45, 69, 56);">üå± Conservation and Respect</h2>

              <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">
                  These waterfalls have survived millions of years of geological time, but they're surprisingly fragile when it comes to human impact. Each year, thousands of visitors come to experience these natural wonders, and it's crucial that we all do our part to preserve them for future generations.
                </p>

                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
                  <div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4" style="color: rgb(86, 125, 95);">‚úÖ Do:</h3>
                    <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                      <li>‚Ä¢ Stay on designated trails</li>
                      <li>‚Ä¢ Pack out all trash</li>
                      <li>‚Ä¢ Observe wildlife from distance</li>
                      <li>‚Ä¢ Visit during off-peak times</li>
                      <li>‚Ä¢ Support local conservation groups</li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>

                  <div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4" style="color: rgb(45, 69, 56);">‚ùå Don't:</h3>
                    <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                      <li>‚Ä¢ Step off designated areas</li>
                      <li>‚Ä¢ Throw anything in waterfalls</li>
                      <li>‚Ä¢ Feed wildlife</li>
                      <li>‚Ä¢ Remove rocks or plants</li>
                      <li>‚Ä¢ Enter water during storms</li>
